"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819120?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 20 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pepper-and-salt-f4e24044</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pepper-and-salt-f4e24044<category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>仅标题内容</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>仅标题内容</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Biden to the Senate: So Su Me]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>总统缺乏确认苏朱莉担任劳工部长的票数，但仍授予她这一职位。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590094361209814860"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590094361209814860"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 19 日晚上 8:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/julie-su-labor-department-senate-bill-cassidy-joe-biden-b8c63a1c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820449?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">四月，朱莉·苏 (Julie Su) 出席在华盛顿国会山举行的参议院健康、教育、劳工和养老金委员会就其劳工部长提名举行的听证会。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿曼达·安德拉德-罗兹/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>西弗吉尼亚州参议员乔·曼钦(Joe Manchin)上周宣布反对拜登总统的进步派劳工部长提名人朱莉·苏(Julie Su)。对不起，参议员。白宫表示，即使参议院不批准苏女士的任命，她也可以领导该部门。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>拜登先生于三月份提名苏女士接替马蒂·沃尔什(Marty Walsh)下台。参议院于 2021 年 7 月根据党派路线投票确认苏女士为副国务卿。然而，部长拥有更大的影响力，包括制定监管议程、批准对企业的指控以及干预劳资谈判的权力。</p><p>苏女士在加州担任劳工部长的经历并不推荐她。她推动了该州 AB5 法的实施，该法将独立承包商重新归类为雇员，包括卡车司机、美甲沙龙工人和自由撰稿人。 2020 年，加州选民投票豁免 Uber 和许多其他零工工人，部分否定了该法律。</p><p>她还支持加州的《快速恢复法案》，该法案授权州委员会决定快餐店员工的工资、福利和工作规则。作为劳工部长，她可以将金州的命令和控制劳工模式推广到全国，这就是拜登提名她的原因。这也是她的提名在参议院受到冷落的原因。</p><p>白宫现在辩称，劳工部继任法允许副部长履行部长职责，“直到任命继任者为止”。这意味着苏女士不需要得到确认就职。正如路易斯安那州参议员比尔·卡西迪在周三给拜登的信中解释的那样，这在法律上是值得怀疑的。</p><p>他指出，《联邦职位空缺改革法案》“对代理官员填补建议和同意职位的时间（210 天）设置了限制”。这一限制的目的是“激励总统及时提交提名，同时也为参议院提供充足的机会来完成其宪法授权。”</p><p>卡西迪写道，白宫似乎正在援引劳工部继任法，“以保护苏女士永久担任代理部长的能力，即使她无法获得参议院确认所需的票数”。 《联邦职位空缺改革法案》旨在阻止总统做拜登现在正在做的事情。</p><p> “我认为，《继承法》的这种使用违反了宪法中关于建议和同意的规定，并可能使苏朱莉领导下的任何劳工部行动面临法律挑战，”他补充道。企业可以对劳工部即将出台的加班规定或苏女士非法服务的工资和工时收费提出质疑。</p><p>根据卡西迪先生的信，当参议院和白宫由同一政党控制时，苏女士等待全体投票的时间比任何内阁级提名人都长。如果她没有得到确认的票数，总统应该提名其他人。这将消除她任期内可能危及该部门行动的法律阴云。</p><p>总统不介意参议院的建议，但他在同意方面遇到了问题。如果拜登坚持藐视参议院，这就是拒绝苏女士提名并面临法律挑战的另一个原因。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 20 Jul 2023 00:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/julie-su-labor-department-senate-bill-cassidy-joe-biden-b8c63a1c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/julie-su-labor-department-senate-bill-cassidy-joe-biden-b8c63a1c<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>白色的房子</category><category>苏朱莉</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Next Target for Ron DeSantis: the Military]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>打文化战争很重要，但为真正的战争做好准备也很重要。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590097890971576632"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590097890971576632"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 6:44 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantis-military-plan-china-defense-culture-wars-pentagon-b3eb2211"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820452?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，佛罗里达州州长兼共和党总统候选人罗恩·德桑蒂斯在南卡罗来纳州西哥伦比亚庆祝自由基金会机库举行的新闻发布会上发表讲话</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：肖恩·雷福德/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">罗恩·德桑蒂斯</a>正在逐步制定他的总统议程，周二他公布了一项建立“使命第一”美国军队的计划。佛罗里达州州长有几个有价值的想法来恢复美国对武装部队的信心，尽管打文化战争并不能代替防止真正的战争。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>南卡罗来纳州州长德桑蒂斯表示：“我们需要一支专注于致命、做好准备和有能力的军队。”随着高级军官急于将自己与进步事业联系起来，美国军队正遭受体制漂移之苦。一个例子：太空部队中将迪安娜·伯特 (DeAnna Burt) 在 6 月的一次演讲中对民选州立法机构考虑她所谓的“反 LGBTQ+”措施发起了政治猛烈攻击。</p><p>重振美国军事教育是一项优先任务。德桑蒂斯州长的观点是正确的，军种学院应该“狭隘地关注”工程或军事历史和领导力等学科。民间学者已经接管了战争学院等大多数军事教育机构，正如德桑蒂斯州长所说，其教学往往“不合格”。</p><p>州长是一名海军退伍军人，他还表示，他将审查每位四星军官的表现，并剔除那些不注重杀伤力的人。我们有理由怀疑，这些军种是否通过根据优点挑选领导人来培养国家所需的作战人才。更积极的民间监督将会有所帮助。</p><p>举个例子：2021 年，一位海军上将建议海军应该带回照片作为宣传板的一部分，以实现更多多样性。州长德桑蒂斯表示，他将禁止“军队招募和晋升中的种族和性别配额”。</p><p>人们认为军队是一个政治机构，这可能会损害征兵工作，而陆军今年可能会短缺至少 10,000 名士兵。德桑蒂斯州长表示，他将在武装部队中“恢复民族自豪感”，其中包括一个学校项目，解释美军“一直是世界上正义和善良的力量”，这至少是一个开始。</p><p>但这些军种难以招募新兵的一个未被充分认识的原因是，这支部队规模太小，而且装备不足，无法完成当前的任务。这使部队疲惫不堪。特朗普总统吹嘘他重建了美国军队，但他提出的一次性军费增加只是开始重建奥巴马总统两届任期内烧毁的战备状态。</p><p>在特朗普的领导下，国防工业基础也继续受到侵蚀。承包商现在正在<a href="https://www.defenseone.com/business/2023/06/raytheon-calls-retirees-help-restart-stinger-missile-production/388067/" target="_blank" class="icon none">召回 70 多岁的退休工程师</a>，教新工人如何制造几十年来一直没有生产的毒刺防空导弹。</p><p>德桑蒂斯州长针对觉醒的特别行动将刺激他的支持者，他正确地将中国视为美国安全的最大威胁。他更艰巨的任务将是为一支规模更大、能力更强的美国军队争取公众支持，以阻止共产党犯下入侵台湾等可怕错误。</p><p>这需要说服持怀疑态度的共和党人增加国防开支——例如，每年为美国海军建造两艘攻击潜艇，从现在的 1.2 艘增加到这一数字。或者加速空军新型战略轰炸机的研制。或者建造可以在台海作战超过三个晚上的远程导弹库存。</p><p>竞选团队的一名助手表示，德桑蒂斯州长仍计划提供更广泛的国防议程。但在美国对乌克兰的支持问题上，他经常迎合孤立主义右翼，用罗纳德·里根的话来说，这种右翼会在一个不无辜的世界里在国外扮演无辜者。</p><p>尽管如此，五角大楼对身份政治的日益关注正在腐蚀一个建立在凝聚力和自我牺牲基础上的机构。如果新总统开始扭转局面，这个国家就能更好地做好战斗准备。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=968EF75F-0B77-4A6F-A6C4-A5C16DD54614&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fron-desantis-military-plan-china-defense-culture-wars-pentagon-b3eb2211&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：随着保守派不再信任联邦调查局，进步自由派不再信任当地警察部队，我们所依赖的保护我们的人正在离开执法部门，犯罪率不断上升。图片：彭博新闻社/祖玛出版社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 22:44:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantis-military-plan-china-defense-culture-wars-pentagon-b3eb2211</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantis-military-plan-china-defense-culture-wars-pentagon-b3eb2211<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>五角大楼</category><category>罗恩·德桑蒂斯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Hunter Biden Whistleblowers]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>国税局特工已公开宣誓。司法部长梅里克·加兰会回应吗？ <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590098440591284762"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590098440591284762"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 6:43 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/irs-whistleblowers-hunter-biden-joseph-ziegler-gary-shapley-merrick-garland-david-weiss-e052e714"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820377?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周三，美国国税局监督特工加里·沙普利（左）和国税局刑事调查部门特工约瑟夫·齐格勒在众议院监督和问责委员会听证会上与国税局举报人一起宣誓就职。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：斯蒂芬妮·斯卡布勒/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>随着时间一天天过去，人们越来越难以相信司法部长梅里克·加兰坚称亨特·拜登案没有受到干预。一个月前，拜登总统的儿子就税收和枪支指控达成了一项协议，这可能意味着不会入狱。现在是周三两名国税局举报人的证词，他们表示，他们调查亨特的努力面临着前所未有的干预。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>两名国税局特工是加里·沙普利和约瑟夫·齐格勒。两个月前，两人都曾在众议院筹款委员会闭门发表讲话，但周三是他们第一次成为众人瞩目的焦点，也是齐格勒先生的名字第一次被公开。</p><p>他们表示，司法部干预了他们的调查，例如，向亨特的法律团队通报了计划中的搜查，并阻止了与乔·拜登有关的问题。他们还表示，国税局团队无法访问亨特的笔记本电脑和/或 FD-1023 文件，其中一名联邦调查局线人声称乔和亨特各自接受了乌克兰能源巨头 Burisma 的 500 万美元贿赂。</p><p>一些民主党人，例如马里兰州的杰米·拉斯金，试图将这一切视为调查人员和检察官之间的正常分歧。但沙普利先生作证说，法官“处理亨特·拜登税务调查的方式与我在国税局工作 14 年来的任何其他案件都非常不同”。</p><p>他们得到了一位新的联邦调查局举报人的支持，这位举报人是一名被派去调查拜登的前监督特工。据众议院监督委员会称，联邦调查局特工周一证实，在他和沙普利计划采访亨特的当天，特工被告知不要接近他，而是等待亨特给他们打电话。采访从未发生过。</p><p>沙普利作证说，在 2022 年 10 月 7 日的一次会议上，负责亨特·拜登调查的美国检察官戴维·韦斯 (David Weiss) 向六名国税局 (IRS) 和联邦调查局 (FBI) 探员承认，他不是决策机构。据沙普利先生说，韦斯先生说他已经申请了特别顾问身份，但被拒绝了。</p><p>韦斯先生的回应言论只会加剧混乱。最近，他声称自己从未申请过特别检察官身份，但他讨论了可能被任命为特别检察官，这将使他“在没有当地美国检察官合作的情况下，在我所在地区以外的地区提出指控”。</p><p>在整个听证会上，民主党人大多选择了“Whataboutism”，而不是向沙普利和齐格勒先生施压要求答案。新墨西哥州众议员梅兰妮·斯坦斯伯里表示，这一证词是对委员会资源的政治浪费。 “真正的罪犯，以及对我们民主制度的真正威胁，是唐纳德·特朗普，”她咆哮道。</p><p>调查亨​​特的美国国税局特工在 C-Span 直播中表示，他们无法获取证据。随着支持这些指控的证人数量的增加，这些指控也变得更加具体。如果加兰先生和韦斯先生想说服美国人他们说的是实话，他们应该去国会并做两位国税局特工现在所做的事情：宣誓回答问题。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E0E5B4F1-87B3-4E8A-97B2-EDDC398CEC81&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Firs-whistleblowers-hunter-biden-joseph-ziegler-gary-shapley-merrick-garland-david-weiss-e052e714&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">可靠的国税局举报人指责司法部阻止亨特·拜登调查的调查人员追踪涉及拜登总统的线索。图片：美联社/祖玛出版社/新闻日报 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 22:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/irs-whistleblowers-hunter-biden-joseph-ziegler-gary-shapley-merrick-garland-david-weiss-e052e714</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/irs-whistleblowers-hunter-biden-joseph-ziegler-gary-shapley-merrick-garland-david-weiss-e052e714<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>举报人</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>联邦调查局</category><category>大卫·韦斯</category><category>加里·沙普利</category><category>约瑟夫·齐格勒</category><category>梅里克·加兰</category><category>亨特·拜登</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>举报人</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The FBI Loses the Public]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>当局长克里斯托弗·雷 (Christopher Wray) 面对国会时，民意调查显示，只有 37% 的人支持该局。共和党人中这一比例为 17%。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590096561738699160"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590096561738699160"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/daniel-henninger"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI552_hennin_AM_20180807121334.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/daniel-henninger" itemprop="url" rel="author">丹尼尔·亨宁格</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 5:45 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fbi-loses-the-public-opinion-la-nyc-trust-crime-order-wray-7166e7d8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=968EF75F-0B77-4A6F-A6C4-A5C16DD54614&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-fbi-loses-the-public-opinion-la-nyc-trust-crime-order-wray-7166e7d8&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：随着保守派不再信任联邦调查局，进步自由派不再信任当地警察部队，我们所依赖的保护我们的人正在离开执法部门，犯罪率不断上升。图片：彭博新闻社/祖玛出版社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div><p>保守派不再信任联邦调查局。自由主义者——或者更准确地说是进步主义者——不再信任当地警察。我们出现了问题。</p><p>国内安全过多与过少之间的紧张关系可以追溯到该国建国之初。在涉及第四修正案保护政府免受无理搜查和扣押的案件中，它经常会诉诸最高法院。这些争论可能很激烈，但最终系统会进行调整。</p><p>现在发生的事情不同了。美国已经陷入了对我们所谓的治理机构的信任危机。执政这个词被认为是理所当然的，但执政却花了很长时间才成为日常生活的事实。考虑一下治理其他地方的反面——混乱、混乱、无政府状态。</p><p>我们可能比我们想象的更接近治理的反面。城市犯罪、盲目和随意的杀戮、帐篷城里的无家可归者、家长在学校董事会上大喊大叫，以及联邦调查局突袭前总统住宅的画面。许多人不但没有做出调整，反而放弃了为国内安宁提供基石的机构。</p><p> <a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/meet-the-press/meetthepressblog/americans-sour-fbi-doj-trump-investigations-rcna91814" target="_blank" class="icon none">NBC 几周前发布的一项民意调查</a>显示，公众对 FBI 的正面看法为 37%。 2018年底，这一比例为52%。联邦调查局局长克里斯托弗·雷可以坐在国会面前，平静地解释共和党人对他的机构的不满，但在我看来，他的组织似乎处于红色区域。在共和党人中，对联邦调查局的支持是。 。 。 17%。无论政治如何，这都不好。</p><p>最近新闻中出现了很多暴力犯罪事件，这让我更多地思考警察或联邦调查局特工的实际行为，而不是这里的党派分歧。正如俗话所说，他们通常所做的就是维持和平。但这种和平需要他们愿意做我们大多数人从未考虑过的事情，或者付出对许多人来说太高的代价。所以我们希望警察能够继续为我们做这件事。但如果他们不这样做怎么办？</p><p>交通堵塞曾经是例行公事。最近没那么多了。上周末，在北达科他州法戈市的一个交通站点，两名警察被枪手打成重伤，一名警察死亡。死者23岁， <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/minnesota/news/well-miss-him-very-much-so-st-michael-classmates-football-coach-mourn-officer-jake-wallin-killed-in-fargo-shootings/" target="_blank" class="icon none">曾是国民警卫队士兵</a>，曾在阿富汗和伊拉克服役。</p><p>几年前，我在伟大的犯罪作家雷蒙德·钱德勒的一本小说中做了标记。一位经验丰富的警官描述了日常生活中的现实。 “我们就是这样，”他说。 “我们一生都在翻着脏内衣，嗅着腐烂的牙齿。我们爬上黑暗的楼梯去拿一袋啤酒花的枪朋克，有时我们无法完全爬上去，我们的妻子那天晚上和其他所有晚上都在等待晚餐。我们不再回家了。晚上我们回家时，我们回到家时太累了，我们吃不下饭，睡不着觉，甚至读不到报纸上关于我们的谎言。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>了解更多仙境</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/-migrant-biden-illegal-undocumented-alien-immigrant-border-wall-desantis-trump-2024-db160555?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">一场破坏性巨大的移民混乱</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 12 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/scapegoating-the-supreme-court-harvard-education-polarization-delegitimization-affirmative-action-3ae75f57?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">最高法院的替罪羊</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 5 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-supreme-court-wrestles-the-rights-monster-debate-decision-views-battle-opinion-18750137?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">最高法院与权利怪物搏斗</a><span class="date">2023 年 6 月 28 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>过去三年里，大约有1000名警察从洛杉矶警察部队辞职或提前退休。据《纽约邮报》 <a href="https://nypost.com/2023/03/10/nypd-cops-resigning-from-force-in-2023-at-record-pace/" target="_blank" class="icon none">报道</a>，预计今年约有 1,400 名纽约警察局警察将在达到退休年龄之前辞职。警察行政研究论坛的一项<a href="https://www.policeforum.org/staffing2023" target="_blank" class="icon none">研究</a>发现，去年全国辞职人数比 2019 年增加了 50%。</p><p>这次飞行的大部分时间是在 2020 年 5 月乔治·弗洛伊德 (George Floyd) 在明尼阿波利斯被杀之后发生的，这导致许多地方当局与其警察部队之间的信任大幅崩溃。关于警务的争论，无论多么有效，都加剧了以前无伤大雅的撤资警察运动。反警察情绪的完美风暴使许多北方城市的居民面临危险。我们都处于危险之中。</p><p>诺贝尔奖获得者小说家 VS 奈保尔用了一生的时间来阐述在文明生活和他所说的“丛林”之间保持界限的重要性。在一次采访中，他将丛林定义为“制度的崩溃，人与人之间契约的崩溃。这是盗窃、腐败、种族主义煽动。”</p><p>这里的要点是，奈保尔的制度崩溃概念可能会发生，而且代价非常高。在遭受帮派蹂躏多年的萨尔瓦多，政府通过警察镇压恢复了和平，这在美国任何地方都是难以想象的，并获得了<a href="https://apnews.com/article/el-salvador-gangs-crackdown-anniversary-4d36f909f9f759d3a57edee47519e562" target="_blank" class="icon none">压倒性的公众支持</a>。</p><p>当双方长时间相互争论而忘记了最初的利害关系或问题时，就会发生制度瓦解。人们有一种上周雷先生和他的共和党提问者之间发生的感觉。</p><p>他想谈论芬太尼团伙、针对儿童的犯罪和中国网络犯罪分子。他应该这样做。但正如联邦法官特里·道蒂最近的裁决所述，他似乎对保守派对联邦调查局参与社交媒体平台言论自由压制的担忧完全不感兴趣。</p><p>雷先生可能认为联邦调查局太大、太重要，不能重蹈正在分崩离析的洛杉矶警察局的覆辙。不要赌它。</p><p><em>写信给 henninger@wsj.com。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 21:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fbi-loses-the-public-opinion-la-nyc-trust-crime-order-wray-7166e7d8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fbi-loses-the-public-opinion-la-nyc-trust-crime-order-wray-7166e7d8<author><![CDATA[Daniel Henninger]]></author><category>犯罪</category><category>联邦调查局</category><category>警察</category><category>公众信任</category><category>法律和秩序</category><category>城市</category><category>舆论</category><category>警察</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>调查/民意调查</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>克里斯托弗·雷</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>调查</category><category>民意调查</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[No Labels Should Worry Democrats]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>有理由认为曼钦式的候选人可以吸引关键的拜登选民。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590098040209728502"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590098040209728502"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/karl-rove" itemprop="url" rel="author">卡尔·罗夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 5:43 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-should-worry-democrats-third-party-trump-biden-swing-7d8fec38"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820089?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2020 年 11 月 3 日，一名投票站工作人员在加利福尼亚州帕科伊马的一所小学外放置了投票标志。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·克兰/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“无标签”标榜自己是一场两党运动，致力于团​​结美国人并治愈我们的政治。但目前情况正在动荡，尤其是在民主党人中间。</p><p>周一，众议员安妮·库斯特（新罕布什尔州民主党人） <a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2023/07/17/no-labels-coming-out-party-00106714" target="_blank" class="icon none">谴责</a>该组织提名第三方总统候选人的计划，称这将为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普的</a>胜利“铺平道路”。民主党重量级人物还宣布成立超级政治行动委员会来对抗“无标签”运动。组织者之一、前众议员托马斯·唐尼 (Thomas Downey) 谴责“无标签”组织的领导是“妄想”，并警告称其计划将“对特朗普有帮助”。</p><p>这些都是合理的担忧。 CNN/SSRS 6 月 17 日的一项民意调查<a href="https://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/23854152/cnn-poll-on-trump-after-2nd-indictment.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">似乎表明</a>，两党领先者不仅彼此不相上下，而且第三种选择也很模糊。虽然 33% 的受访者对特朗普有好感，32% 的受访者对拜登有好感，但 31% 的受访者对他们都不看好。</p><p>因此，如果拜登和特朗普是各自政党的提名人，那么“无标签”的有力竞争者可能会影响结果。其中一位可能的候选人是西弗吉尼亚州民主党参议员乔·曼钦(Joe Manchin)，他周一在新罕布什尔州该组织的市政厅亮相。毫无疑问，涉及曼钦的三方竞争将加剧拜登团队与关键群体的问题，首先是令人失望的群体——对拜登不感兴趣的两批民主党人。</p><p>其中一个重要群体由 18 至 29 岁的选民组成。2020 年，他们占选民的 17%（约 2690 万选民），拜登的比例突破了 60%，特朗普的比例突破了 36%。与 2018 年相比，2022 年中期选举中年轻选民的投票率有所下降，民主党的投票率也略有下降，从而帮助共和党推翻了众议院。继续强调大学债务减免和气候问题不足以重振失望的年轻选民的活力。到目前为止还没有发挥作用。一些年轻的民主党倾向选民可能会喜欢“无标签”对两党合作和明智变革的强调。</p><p>然后是黑人选民。 5 月 12 日《华盛顿邮报》/益普索 (Ipsos) 民意调查发现，如果拜登连任，只有 17% 的黑人会表现出热情，而 49% 的人表示他的政策对他们“没有影响”，14% 的人表示他们受到了“伤害”。他们。此外，与 2018 年相比，2022 年黑人投票率有所下降，2021 年 1 月至 2023 年 3 月期间，拜登在黑人选民中的支持率下降了 10 个百分点。拜登团队表面上的解决方案——关注选民权利——并不能保证总统的支持率提升。再说一次，如果这行得通的话，它已经行得通了。</p><p>缺乏热情有什么关系吗？绝对地。如果拜登在佐治亚州的黑人支持者中有 1.1% 明年留在家里或投票“无标签”，那么他在 2020 年桃州的胜利优势即 11,779 票将被抹去。如果拜登在亚利桑那州的年轻支持者中只有 6.3% 的人明年留在家里或投票“无标签”，那么他在 2020 年大峡谷州的胜利优势为 10,457 点。</p><p>然后是三组潜在的民主党叛逃者，其中一些人可能会被承诺变革、强调两党合作并专注于让政府运转的中间派“无标签”平台所吸引。拉美裔选民的比例不断右移，从 2016 年的 11% 上升到 2020 年的 13%。亚裔美国选民也一直右倾。无标签选票可能会吸引拉美裔和亚裔选民，他们不再是民主党人，但不愿支持特朗普。</p><p>还有郊区的独立人士，包括被特朗普拒之门外的前共和党人。他们在 2018 年和 2022 年与表现不佳的共和党候选人一起投票给民主党，他们还在 2020 年让拜登入主白宫。他需要他们再次获胜。</p><p>考虑 2020 年最接近的三个州。特朗普以总选票的 0.31% 输掉了亚利桑那州，而共和党国会候选人总共以 0.28% 的优势获胜，比他的领先优势高出 0.59 个百分点。特朗普以 0.24% 的差距输掉了佐治亚州，而共和党国会候选人以 2% 的优势获胜，相差 2.24 个百分点。他以 0.63% 的差距输掉了威斯康星州，而共和党国会候选人以 2.93% 的优势获胜，比前总统高出 3.56 个百分点。如果拜登先生未能影响倾向共和党的分票者，并在这些州获得与民主党美国众议院候选人相同的百分比，他将失去所有三个州和选举。一张带有里根式共和党人的无标签选票可能会吸引足够多的右倾摇摆选民，将这些关系密切的州从民主党阵营中移出。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》的专栏作家威廉·高尔斯顿 (William Galston) 是六次民主党总统竞选的资深人士，也是比尔·克林顿 (Bill Clinton) 的前顾问。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-will-make-2024-even-worse-manchin-third-party-trump-biden-ticket-95870b2f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他本周表示</a>，“无标签”可以“大幅增加特朗普当选的机会”，这是正确的。但出于我下周将探讨的原因，共和党人也应该担心“无标签”问题。这也威胁到了他们的机会。</p><p><em>罗夫先生帮助组织了政治行动委员会“美国十字路口”，并且是《威廉·麦金利的胜利》（Simon &amp; Schuster，2015 年）一书的作者。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B8964F58-095C-4932-AB1E-4E5335D914B0&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fno-labels-should-worry-democrats-third-party-trump-biden-swing-7d8fec38&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报道：保罗·吉戈特采访道格·舍恩。图片：Getty Images/CNP/Zuma Press 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 21:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-should-worry-democrats-third-party-trump-biden-swing-7d8fec38</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-should-worry-democrats-third-party-trump-biden-swing-7d8fec38<author><![CDATA[Karl Rove]]></author><category>摇摆选民</category><category>摇摆州</category><category>独立人士</category><category>第三者</category><category>没有标签</category><category>2024 年选举</category><category>拉丁裔</category><category>亚裔美国人</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Life Hack, if You Can Keep It]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>查德教会了我生活窍门和遵循指示的价值。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11760920926854734166704590042113662859960"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11760920926854734166704590042113662859960"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">迈克·克里根</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 5:42 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-life-hack-if-you-can-keep-it-efficiency-tricks-tips-travel-shoes-46c1cac2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-806666?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>几年前，当一位同事使用“生活黑客”这个词时，我承认我很陌生。从上下文中可以清楚地看出，她指的是一条聪明的捷径，但我从来没有用这个名字或任何其他名字来称呼它，尤其是当我可以简单地称呼我的朋友查德时。</p><p>查德是我认识三十多年的人，他是一位行走的生活黑客。他认真对待苏格拉底的主张，即未经审视的生活不值得过，并考虑了做大多数事情的最精明的方法。最近我有机会想起他的一个栗子。</p><p>我飞往伦敦的红眼航班于黎明时分降落。与我会面的同事约翰比我晚两小时从亚特兰大起飞。我从希思罗机场坐车到酒店，办理入住手续并等待约翰的到来。</p><p>我们面临的挑战是要保持两个小时的清醒状态，以免耽误工作日。我记得查德在我们大学时代的教导之一：只脱掉一只鞋子和一只袜子，但另一只袜子穿上并且鞋子紧紧地系紧时，是不可能入睡的。</p><p>我脱掉左鞋和袜子，把右鞋的结系紧，自信地躺在床上。我几乎立刻就睡着了。值得庆幸的是，我把 iPhone 放在胸前，所以当约翰在去伦敦的路上打电话给我时，我醒了。没有损失一个工作日。</p><p>查德通常聪明的建议遭到前所未有的失败，我感到很失望，回到家后我给他打了电话。 “查德，”我开始说道，“我在经过一夜的飞行后一回到酒店房间就尝试了你脱掉鞋子和袜子的技巧来保持清醒。它不起作用。是什么赋予了？”</p><p> “开车，”他澄清道。 “开车时脱掉一只鞋子和一只袜子有助于保持清醒。”然后，闻着血腥味，“你真的认为你可以脱掉鞋子，在红眼后撞到架子上而不睡着吗？”我没有用答案来严肃地回答这个问题，因为这是一个可怜的工匠指责他的工具，尤其是当他用锯子作为锤子时。</p><p>生活黑客的好坏取决于生活黑客遵循指示的能力。为了确保这种情况总是发生，我会打电话给乍得。</p><p> <em>Kerrigan 先生是北卡罗来纳州夏洛特市的一名律师</em></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B89B2690-0317-40F9-A22B-4C9D280DCCCC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-life-hack-if-you-can-keep-it-efficiency-tricks-tips-travel-shoes-46c1cac2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊编辑报告：金·斯特拉塞尔 (Kim Strassel)、比尔·麦格恩 (Bill McGurn)、玛丽·奥格雷迪 (Mary O&#39;Grady) 和丹·亨宁格 (Dan Henninger) 分享了本周最好和最差的内容。图片来源：美联社/EPA/Shutterstock/Reuters/Zuma Press 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 21:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-life-hack-if-you-can-keep-it-efficiency-tricks-tips-travel-shoes-46c1cac2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-life-hack-if-you-can-keep-it-efficiency-tricks-tips-travel-shoes-46c1cac2<category>飞机场</category><category>生活窍门</category><category>袜子</category><category>鞋</category><category>工匠</category><category>效率</category><category>旅行</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The People’s Justice’ Review: The Originalist and the Masses]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一位联邦法官认为，当我们遵循宪法文本时，弱者和无权者将受益最多。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590087933842749418"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820320?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">最高法院法官克拉伦斯·托马斯。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：罗德·艾德洛特/韦科论坛先驱报/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590087933842749418"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">大卫·J·加罗</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 19 日下午 5:41 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-peoples-justice-review-the-originalist-and-the-masses-d683b2fa"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>当美国最高法院最近的任期结束时，彭博社法强调了 75 岁的克拉伦斯·托马斯法官在担任高位法官 32 年的过程中，“从局外人变成了保守派多数派的意识形态领袖”。特别是，法院以 6 比 2 的裁决禁止大学招生中的种族偏好，这是托马斯法官职业生涯的历史性“顶峰”。</p><p>早在他从事司法工作之前，他就对种族问题抱有坚定的看法，因为即使在 1969 年，他还是圣十字学院的一名本科生时，他就要求“从白人——无论是有意还是无意——坚持强加给黑人的奴役中彻底解放出来。”托马斯大法官在其司法服务初期就援引了同样的原则，并在 1995 年的一份意见中宣称，“种族家长作风及其意想不到的后果可能与任何其他形式的歧视一样有毒和有害。”正如他后来告诉黑人律师团体的那样，“用种族来定义我们每个人”“无异于否认我们的人性”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><p><strong>人民正义</strong></p><p><em>作者：阿穆尔·塔帕尔</em></p><p><em>（Regnery Gateway，273 页，32.99 美元）</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/bf156263-6ef9-49a7-a597-009b4c760dc7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>阿穆尔·塔帕尔 (Amul Thapar) 是美国第六巡回上诉法院的法官。现年 54 岁的他被广泛认为是未来由共和党总统任命的最高法院的最佳竞争者，他在业余时间写了《人民正义》，这是对托马斯大法官判例的令人信服的致敬，旨在强调他的“真实的性格”和他所说的“托马斯巨大的勇气”。 Judge Thapar, like Justice Thomas, identifies as an originalist, explaining that “the core idea behind originalism is honoring the will of the people” as expressed both in the Constitution and in legislatively enacted statutes by venerating “what the words of those documents meant when they were enacted.” He identifies Justice Thomas as “the most powerful originalist voice of our day” and contends that “when we actually follow the original meaning of the Constitution, the weak and the politically powerless stand to benefit the most.”</p><p> Judge Thapar offers a dozen short, engaging histories of cases in which Justice Thomas authored an opinion, focusing on the participants&#39; stories rather than the justice&#39;s reasoning. Some are obscure, such as a pair of rape cases that the Supreme Court declined to hear but in which Justice Thomas nonetheless wrote in advocacy of the two victims&#39; claims. But most strongly support Judge Thapar&#39;s argument.</p><p> In 1999 in <em>City of Chicago v. Morales</em> , a 6-3 Court majority struck down a Chicago loitering ordinance targeting street-gang members as unconstitutionally vague. Justice Thomas dissented, arguing that “gangs fill the daily lives of many of our poorest and most vulnerable citizens with a terror that the Court does not give sufficient consideration.” He pointedly emphasized that “the people who will have to live with the consequences of today&#39;s opinion do not live in our neighborhoods.”</p><p> In 2002 in <em>Zelman v. Simmons-Harris</em> , a 5-4 majority, including Justice Thomas, narrowly upheld a school-voucher program enacted by the city of Cleveland. Justice Thomas&#39;s concurrence highlighted how “the promise of public school education has failed poor inner-city blacks.”</p><p> The next year, in <em>Virginia v. Black</em> , the Court rejected on free-speech grounds the prosecution of a Ku Klux Klan leader for burning a cross. Justice Thomas dissented, noting how state legislators had first enacted a ban on cross-burning “with the intent to intimidate” during the height of Jim Crow: “Even segregationists understood the difference between intimidating and terroristic conduct and racist expression.”</p><p> In 2003, in <em>Grutter v. Bollinger</em> , the Court grudgingly upheld the University of Michigan Law School&#39;s affirmative-action admissions program, with Justice Sandra Day O&#39;Connor writing that “we expect that 25 years from now, the use of racial preferences will no longer be necessary” to achieve a diverse student body. Dissenting, Justice Thomas argued that the Constitution “means the same thing today as it will in 300 months” and complained that Michigan “seeks only a facade” of diversity while championing policies that will “stamp minorities with a badge of inferiority.”</p><p> When <em>Students for Fair Admissions v. Harvard</em> was announced on June 29, Justice Thomas presented his long concurring opinion from the bench. He labeled it “an originalist defense of the colorblind Constitution.” In <em>Brown v. Board of Education</em> (1954), he pointed out, legendary civil-rights lawyer and future justice Thurgood Marshall argued that “the Constitution is color blind is our dedicated belief.”</p><p> “All racial categories are little more than stereotypes, suggesting that immutable characteristics somehow conclusively determine a person&#39;s ideology, beliefs, and abilities,” Justice Thomas wrote. Thus racial preferences “strip us of our individuality and undermine the very diversity of thought that universities purport to seek.”</p><p> Justice Thomas&#39;s <em>Harvard</em> opinion unsurprisingly validates Judge Thapar&#39;s overarching theme in “The People&#39;s Justice.” It bears emphasis too that among appellate jurists Judge Thapar is far from alone in his outspoken admiration of Justice Thomas&#39;s jurisprudence. Another elegant encomium was penned some years ago by now-retired New York Court of Appeals judge Robert S. Smith in the NYU Journal of Law &amp; Liberty. Surveying a raft of sometimes arcane Thomas opinions, Judge Smith opined that “Thomas seems at times to display more analytical rigor than his colleagues” and asked, “Why does it seem, repeatedly, that Justice Thomas has simply out-thought his colleagues on a purely technical, analytical issue? I really don&#39;t know.”</p><p> Judge Smith, like Judge Thapar, had a bigger target in mind, calling out “politically correct people who have never read a Justice Thomas opinion but are quite sure that he is an evil man.” Aimed at the general reader, “The People&#39;s Justice” will disprove such notions if it&#39;s read by those most in need of its message, and Judge Smith memorably described the educational effort that is slowly but increasingly taking place: “I enjoy seeing certain of my liberal friends scream and gag when I tell them that I think Justice Thomas is one of the greatest Justices who ever sat on the Supreme Court.” Amul Thapar must certainly share that pleasure.</p><p> <em>Mr. Garrow&#39;s latest book is “Rising Star: The Making of Barack Obama.”</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 21:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-peoples-justice-review-the-originalist-and-the-masses-d683b2fa</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-peoples-justice-review-the-originalist-and-the-masses-d683b2fa<category> Books</category><category> Political/General News</category><category> Arts/Entertainment</category><category> Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category> Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> books</category><category> political</category><category> general news</category><category> arts</category><category> entertainment</category><category> content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category> reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Oppenheimer’ Review: Christopher Nolan’s Explosive Historical Epic]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Cillian Murphy plays the father of the atomic bomb in a haunting biopic also starring Robert Downey Jr. and Matt Damon <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590097970408044094"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820036?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cillian Murphy</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Universal Pictures </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590097970408044094"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">凯尔·史密斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">July 19, 2023 5:15 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/oppenheimer-review-christopher-nolan-cillian-murphy-robert-downey-jr-atomic-bomb-be4ffc00"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> “This isn&#39;t a new weapon. It&#39;s a new world,” someone remarks as J. Robert Oppenheimer develops the atomic bomb in “Oppenheimer,” a brainy and breathless exploration of the rise and fall of a physicist dubbed, not without reason, “the most important man who ever lived.” Like Prometheus, the mythic figure to whom he is compared here, Oppenheimer suffered for his works, bedeviled from within and without. So a story that is essentially about a scientist who spent his life writing equations becomes, in the expert hands of writer-director Christopher Nolan, a boiling cauldron of drama.</p><p> Mr. Nolan&#39;s utterly enthralling film lasts three hours. But despite being as talky as a math seminar, it crackles, hurtles and whooshes, generating more suspense and excitement than anything found in the alleged climaxes of the recent superhero pictures (which owe much to the director&#39;s Batman films). Adapting “American Prometheus,” the Pulitzer Prize-winning biography by Kai Bird and Martin J. Sherwin, Mr. Nolan has thought intensely about how to turn arcane material—not one person in 100 could explain the details of Oppenheimer&#39;s method—into a popcorn movie, despite it containing only one spectacular scene.</p><p> “Oppenheimer” is divided into two parts. One is “Fission” (events as seen by the title figure, intensely brought to life by Cillian Murphy with grave arrogance). The other, “Fusion,” is set off by black-and-white imagery and centered on the scientist&#39;s antagonist years after the war, a political figure named Lewis Strauss played by Robert Downey Jr. , who puts his considerable charm on hold and assumes a startling midcentury look. Characteristically, Mr. Nolan chops up time to tell a nonlinear story, keeping most scenes to only a few minutes, as he wanders through the imaginations and memories of these two figures, one of whom perhaps does not deserve quite so much attention. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820026?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Robert Downey Jr. and Mr. Murphy</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Universal Pictures</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> There&#39;s no question which part of the film is more dynamic and involving: The study of Oppenheimer&#39;s life, the development of the bomb and his accompanying self-flagellation about what he unleashed are all magnificently realized. Mr. Nolan does not get enough credit for his writing, but his screenplay should be taught in film schools. He turns abstractions into easily grasped images (at the Los Alamos laboratory, a large glass bowl gradually fills with marbles to indicate US progress toward reaching its goal for enriched uranium), illustrates character in memorable yet succinct ways (Oppenheimer demonstrates genius when he visits Europe to give a physics lecture, opens his mouth and speaks fluent Dutch, a language he did not know weeks earlier), and packs both meaning and wit into crystalline lines of dialogue. The Danish physicist Niels Bohr ( Kenneth Branagh ) is revered among specialists, but to explain his importance to the rest of us, Mr. Nolan has someone ask, “How many people do you know who proved Einstein wrong?” Many of Mr. Nolan&#39;s most sparkling lines go to the general overseeing the Manhattan Project, delightfully played by Matt Damon as the avatar of the try-anything American who combines easygoing confidence with self-deprecation: “I wasn&#39;t confused before, but I&#39;m certainly getting there,” he says, speaking for some in the audience. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="489" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820019?width=700&amp;height=489" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mr. Murphy</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Universal Pictures </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多电影评论</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/barbie-review-margot-robbie-greta-gerwig-ryan-gosling-mattel-256b6688?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Barbie&#39; Review: Beyond Her Ken</a> <span class="date">July 18, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/20-days-in-mariupol-review-inside-ukraines-living-hell-11700795?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《马里乌波尔 20 天》评论：走进乌克兰的人间地狱</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 13 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-miracle-club-review-kathy-bates-laura-linney-maggie-smith-3e149051?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《奇迹俱乐部》评论：宽恕朝圣</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 13 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mission-impossibledead-reckoning-part-one-review-real-tom-cruise-ai-enemy-90de75d4?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《碟中谍4：航位推测第一部分》评论：真正的汤姆·克鲁斯，人工智能敌人</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 11 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>The interspersed other part of the film is not as compelling, though Mr. Nolan evidently feels it depicts a major injustice vital to understanding Oppenheimer and his times. The chief drama here is the 1954 decision of the Atomic Energy Commission, amid a Red Scare, not to renew Oppenheimer&#39;s security clearance after questioning his (many) ties to Communists, a matter linked to a betrayal by Strauss and the latter&#39;s own failure to be confirmed in 1959 as secretary of commerce—the first Senate rejection of a cabinet appointee since 1925. Each of these situations triggers an ersatz trial, hence lots of courtroom-style sparring. But considering Oppenheimer&#39;s mammoth creation, the details surrounding the withdrawal of a security clearance (a decision reversed posthumously just last year) and the fate of an obscure cabinet appointee seem like grains of sand compared to a mountain. Moreover, Mr. Nolan doesn&#39;t sufficiently clarify the motives behind Strauss&#39;s Judas turn. (A dispute over exporting radioactive isotopes is involved, though you may miss it.)</p><p> Such choices do not, however, prevent “Oppenheimer” from being one of the few standout works of cinema released this decade. Its centerpiece—the July 16, 1945, Trinity test in the New Mexico desert that proved both that the bomb worked and that it would not set the entire world afire—generates a level of awe, based in historical pre-eminence rather than fantasy, that we rarely experience at the movies anymore. Amid the ensuing celebration of the grim deployment in Japan of the two A-bombs, instruments of slaughter that nevertheless probably saved hundreds of thousands of lives, Mr. Nolan beautifully captures what was going on inside Oppenheimer&#39;s tortured mind: pride, triumph, horror.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 21:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/oppenheimer-review-christopher-nolan-cillian-murphy-robert-downey-jr-atomic-bomb-be4ffc00</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/oppenheimer-review-christopher-nolan-cillian-murphy-robert-downey-jr-atomic-bomb-be4ffc00<category> arts in review</category><category> Political/General News</category><category>名人</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category> Living/Lifestyle</category><category>电影</category><category>Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category> Reviews</category><category> Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> political</category><category> general news</category><category>名人</category><category>arts</category><category> entertainment</category><category> living</category><category> lifestyle</category><category>电影</category><category>content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category> reviews </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Octavia E. Butler’s Parable of the Sower’ Review: Lost in Operatic Translation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> At Lincoln Center, Toshi Reagon and Bernice Johnson Reagon&#39;s adaptation of the sci-fi novel about a teenager in a crumbling world turns an arresting book into a tedious cross between a song cycle and a harangue. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590094300258527486"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819278?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Marie Tattie Aqeel and the company of &#39;Octavia E. Butler&#39;s Parable of the Sower&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Erin Patrice O&#39;Brien </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590094300258527486"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Heidi Waleson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 4:58 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/octavia-e-butlers-parable-of-the-sower-review-lincoln-center-1538641a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>纽约</p><p>Under the leadership of Shanta Thake since 2021, Lincoln Center has taken a radical turn away from classical programming in a bid to attract new audiences. This year, its two-month “Summer for the City” lineup includes hip-hop, Korean indie rock, and traditional Cuban dance in both indoor and outdoor venues; much of the programming is free or choose-what-you-pay. The lone remnant of summers past is the Mostly Mozart Festival Orchestra, in its final season under that name with its longtime music director Louis Langrée. Next year, the ensemble will have a new leader, Jonathon Heyward, and an identity to be determined.</p><p> On July 13 in David Geffen Hall, Lincoln Center presented the first of three performances of “ Octavia E. Butler&#39;s Parable of the Sower,” dubbed an opera by its creators Toshi Reagon and Bernice Johnson Reagon. Running two hours and 15 minutes without intermission, this sprawling, minimally staged event was a cross between a song cycle and a harangue, riffing on themes and plot points from Butler&#39;s celebrated 1993 Afrofuturist novel. Audience members unfamiliar with the book may well have been confused about the story, because the show&#39;s main character was Toshi Reagon—guitar in hand, positioned on a raised platform at the center of the stage, flanked by vocalists Helga Davis and Shelley Nicole —who acted as narrator, leader, backup singer and haranguer-in-chief. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="468" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819275?width=700&amp;height=468" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Shelley Nicole, Toshi Reagon and Helga Davis</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Lawrence Sumulong</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Butler&#39;s arresting book, set in California in 2024, unfolds in a dystopian world. Climate change has led to privation, rampant violence, and an autocratic government that is in league with corporate interests. Fifteen-year-old Lauren Olamina and her family live in Robledo, a barricaded suburb of Los Angeles. Her Baptist preacher father urges faith and patience, but Lauren, who feels the stirrings of a new religious conviction, insists that the people need to learn to live off the land and prepare to flee. When an attack on the town leaves most of the residents dead, Lauren and two other survivors join the stream of refugees heading north; they dodge threats and gradually assemble a new community around them. One of their number, Bankole, brings them to land he owns in Northern California. They establish a commune, Acorn, and Lauren develops the tenets of her religion, which she calls Earthseed, whose principal mantra is “God is change.”</p><p> The opera invoked Butler&#39;s ideas without capturing any of their nuance or drama. Part I, which takes place in Robledo, was a string of songs that set up the disagreement between Lauren (Marie Tatti Aqeel) and her father ( Jared Wayne Gladly ). Lyrics were not always intelligible, and the amplified volume, aided by a five-member instrumental ensemble that lurked upstage in the darkness, was high, but the tunes were catchy, and the gospel-infused numbers for the congregation (featuring Josette Newsam as a pink-hatted church lady) were deliberately different from Lauren&#39;s independent pop stylings and the mild rap of her rebellious brother Keith (Isaiah Stanley). The dramaturgy, however, was limited. Nothing much happened; it was not entirely clear what role each of the 11 actors was playing; and the direction by Signe Harriday and Eric Ting had the performers mill indiscriminately around a few curved benches and make the occasional foray into the theater aisles. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819274?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The company of &#39;Octavia E. Butler&#39;s Parable of the Sower&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Lawrence Sumulong</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> After about an hour of this, Ms. Reagon broke in with a speech, citing connections between Butler&#39;s 30-year-old predictions and actual present-day woes, including climate change, police brutality, gentrification and the dominance of Amazon, for starters. She then embarked on a strophic blues tune with the refrain, “Don&#39;t let your baby go to Olivar,” which pounded these themes for about 15 minutes, with the audience invited to join in on the chorus. (In the novel, Olivar is a town that has been taken over by a corporation and is luring frightened Californians into slavery with promises of jobs and security. Only readers of the book would know this, however.) </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Opera Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/treemonisha-susannah-and-marcantonio-e-cleopatra-reviews-fatal-love-and-outcasts-arias-36419933?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Treemonisha,&#39; &#39;Susannah&#39; and &#39;Marc&#39;Antonio e Cleopatra&#39; Reviews: Fatal Love and Outcasts&#39; Arias</a> <span class="date">June 27, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dido-and-aeneas-review-roman-tragedy-in-barcelona-e996c140?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Dido and Aeneas&#39; Review: Roman Tragedy in Barcelona</a> <span class="date">June 20, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/die-zauberflote-review-the-met-humanizes-mozarts-fantasy-c84dabba?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Die Zauberflöte&#39; Review: The Met Humanizes Mozart&#39;s Fantasy</a> <span class="date">May 22, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/don-giovanni-review-ivo-van-hoves-grim-mozart-at-the-met-80e69ff0?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Don Giovanni&#39; Review: Ivo van Hove&#39;s Grim Mozart at the Met</a> <span class="date">May 8, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> Part 2 began with the attack on Robledo. There were loud noises in the darkness, people fell to the ground, and a semicircular white cloth that had been hanging above the stage fell—that was the town&#39;s wall. Ms. Aqeel sang the most affecting number of the evening—a wailed lament for Lauren&#39;s lost father, adding more elaborate ornamentation with each new verse. With most of the performers playing different (though still unclear) roles, the journey north had them wandering around in the darkness with flashlights ( Christopher Kuhl designed the lighting, Arnulfo Maldonado the set, Dede M. Ayite the costumes). Songs blended together and the plot, even with a bit of narration dropped in from Ms. Reagon, had even less clarity than in the first half. The conclusion came out of nowhere, and a large community chorus dashed onstage from the audience to sing a final tune referring to Lauren&#39;s mantra, “God is Change,” and then followed it up with a song called “Sower.”</p><p> The packed house (albeit with some defectors over the course of the evening) gave “Parable” a standing ovation; the show felt like a communal exhortation, with Ms. Reagon whipping up the crowd with simplistic tropes. It certainly attracted a young, diverse audience, one that probably won&#39;t be clamoring for tickets when Mr. Langrée conducts Mozart&#39;s Mass in C minor on July 25 and 26. If that is Lincoln Center&#39;s main goal, “Parable” was a success. As an artistic offering, commensurate with the mission of a nonprofit presenter, it fell short.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ms. Waleson writes on opera for the Journal and is the author of “Mad Scenes and Exit Arias: The Death of the New York City Opera and the Future of Opera in America” (Metropolitan).</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 20:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/octavia-e-butlers-parable-of-the-sower-review-lincoln-center-1538641a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/octavia-e-butlers-parable-of-the-sower-review-lincoln-center-1538641a<category> arts in review</category><category> Books</category><category> Political/General News</category><category> Arts/Entertainment</category><category> Music</category><category> Opera</category><category> Theater</category><category> Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category> Reviews</category><category> Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> books</category><category> political</category><category> general news</category><category> arts</category><category> entertainment</category><category> music</category><category> opera</category><category> theater</category><category> content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category> reviews </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Play and Pastimes in the Middle Ages’ Review: A Winning Look at History]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A show of manuscripts at the Getty Center depicting medieval puzzles, games and jousts reveals diversions that, like chess, span our radically different lives and times. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590083990744528262"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820314?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;The God of Love Leads a Dance&#39; (detail, c. 1405), by an unknown artist</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Getty Museum </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590083990744528262"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/edward-rothstein" itemprop="url" rel="author">Edward Rothstein</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 4:49 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/play-and-pastimes-in-the-middle-ages-review-a-winning-look-at-history-b6f89ae"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>Los Angeles</em></p><p> In some ways, the subject of the Getty Center&#39;s exhibition “Play and Pastimes in the Middle Ages” might seem a bit peculiar. Play and pastimes in the world of the Black Death? In towns where sewage streamed in the streets? When people were lucky if their lives were only nasty, brutish and short? Of course there were also those possessing more privilege and power—but who today would readily change places with any of them, let alone think of their bloody games of thrones as mere play? </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>Play and Pastimes in the Middle Ages</strong></p><p> <em>The Getty Center, through Aug. 6</em></p></div></div><p> Yet in this modest but suggestive exhibition—created by Nava Streiter, a former graduate intern at the Getty Museum, with assistance from a senior museum curator, Elizabeth Morrison—we begin to suspect that many of our notions of play may have their origins in those darker times. In some 20 manuscript examples from the Getty&#39;s collection, dating from around 1240 to 1570, we see images and painted illuminations: women being led in decorous dance by the God of Love (French, c. 1405), children playing a board game resembling checkers (French, c. 1320-25), children jousting atop wine barrels (Flemish, before 1465-c. 1541). There are chess puzzles from the late 1300s (Northern France) and allusions to games of love and games of battle.</p><p> Many of these images also show something important about the nature of play as it developed in the West. Though games like checkers and chess have evolutionary origins in the East—in India and the Arab lands—they took modern form in this era. The hierarchical character of chess even has a medieval feel with its rooks and knights and bishops exerting their varied powers to protect their own interests and their king&#39;s. And more than six centuries later, such games remain largely unchanged.</p><p> So familiar are these varieties of play that the exhibition explicitly addresses the contemporary game-player, both child and adult. Checker pieces are supplied for visitors&#39; use on a painted checker board (ornamented with a 14th-century image of similar play). A vast number of this period&#39;s other pastimes find immediate resonance for anybody who has ever played video games (which often invoke medieval themes) or read fantasy fiction (which typically creates variations on medieval cultures) or joined sports teams (which joust over contested terrain). </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="410" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820316?width=700&amp;height=410" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Initial C: The Massacre of the Innocents&#39; (detail, c. 1320-25), by an unknown artist</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Getty Museum</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A remarkable book on display—“The Flower of Battle” in Italian (c. 1410)—deftly presents images showing varieties of lance attacks and defenses; it is actually consulted by players today who, in costume, re-create medieval jousting competitions. Painted on the wall here, enlarged to life size, is a jousting knight on horseback, his lance poised for attack, reproduced from the displayed ”Tournament Book” (Germany, c. 1560-70). “Surely You Joust?” reads the show&#39;s comic-strip bubble painted above the knight. “Like modern sports teams, jousters in the Middle Ages were identified by different colors, patterns and symbols.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Exhibition Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-louis-armstrong-center-review-jazzs-king-in-queens-cac8057c?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">The Louis Armstrong Center Review: Jazz&#39;s King in Queens</a> <span class="date">July 18, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/norman-foster-review-from-blueprints-to-modern-marvels-8d8c9301?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Norman Foster&#39; Review: From Blueprints to Modern Marvels</a> <span class="date">July 12, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/africa-fashion-review-a-continents-creativity-1a50a366?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Africa Fashion&#39; Review: A Continent&#39;s Creativity</a> <span class="date">July 5, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/raphael-born-architect-review-a-masters-foundations-c67a43b0?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Raphael. Born Architect&#39; Review: A Renaissance Master&#39;s Foundations</a> <span class="date">June 14, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> But why should the games we play be so medievalesque given our radically different societies and cultures? The exhibition notes that in the Middle Ages “play created potent imaginative spaces where people could learn skills, experience romance, engage in competition, establish social hierarchies, or simply have fun.” But that is true of all play, in any age. This exhibition doesn&#39;t lead us far enough to be able to discern much more. Even the 14th-century chess problems could have been presented in modern notation so they might be more easily examined. We might have been led further, too, had the explanatory texts not been so cursory.</p><p> But there is also enough here to reveal the peculiarities of these games. While the medieval character of chess is evident, for example, it is also true that even the lowliest pawn can attain royal status (by making its way to the opposition&#39;s side of the board). And though all checkers are initially alike in their powers, they too can attain royal standing (“King me!” is the child&#39;s cry as the checker doubles its stature and power). These games cannot claim a democratic character, but they promise that the victor&#39;s title will be gained by skill, practice and knowledge—not by birth.</p><p> Could it be that this is an aspect of their enduring allure? A game shapes a world of contention with its rules and procedures, its territories and weaponry. And while chess and checkers might seem to echo medieval exercises of power and conquest, in important ways they displace feudal hierarchy, honoring another kind of order. They are games of power, but also games of dissent, providing the first signs of a culture that would eventually learn to value mastery of knowledge and technique, that would celebrate the value of focused attention and envision a hierarchy of achievement rather than of birth. Such games are the forerunners of democratic modernity.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Rothstein is the Journal&#39;s Critic-at-Large.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 20:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/play-and-pastimes-in-the-middle-ages-review-a-winning-look-at-history-b6f89ae</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/play-and-pastimes-in-the-middle-ages-review-a-winning-look-at-history-b6f89ae<author><![CDATA[Edward Rothstein]]></author><category> arts in review</category><category> Political/General News</category><category> Mind Sports</category><category> Arts/Entertainment</category><category>运动的</category><category>Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category> Routine General News</category><category> Revie